Key takeaways.

The binary search tree property — left subtree smaller, right subtree larger — holds recursively at every node, not just at direct children.

In-order traversal always produces sorted output. This is a direct consequence of the ordering rule.

Search, insert, and delete are all proportional to the tree height — logarithmic on a balanced tree, linear on a degenerate one.

The minimum is the leftmost node, the maximum is the rightmost. The in-order successor is the minimum of the right subtree. Deletion has three cases: remove a leaf directly, promote a single child, or replace a two-child node with its in-order successor. And you validate a binary search tree by threading a valid range through the recursion — not by checking only immediate children.
